@carmstrong I updated this PR this morning such that `deisctl refresh-units` also refreshes the decorators that we have discussed.  One interesting question this raises for me is how to deal with the possibility that someone runs `deisctl refresh-units` with the `-t` / `--tag` option to call out a specific tag or commit.  It's probably remote, but there's a possibility that someone can call out an older tag or a commit that does _not_ contain the decorators, resulting in 404s.

I wanted to get your take on how to deal with that, because I think this question had to have come up before-- anytime a _new_ component has been added, you may have run into the same dilemma, although I don't see any specific logic in `deisctl` meant to handle this possibility.

The way I'm currently choosing to deal with this is to gracefully handle and 404s that occur when refreshing the decorators.  Does that sound ok?  Or, alternatively, am I overthinking this and should I just not worry about this?  I tend to imagine that `-t` / `--tag` option is used rather infrequently and only by power users at that.

