@sirdodger No problem about the already-fixed report. Better to err on the side of too many reports than too few (within reason I suppose).

Regarding `gettz`, if you are going to manually manage the zoneinfo files by generating them yourself when upstream changes take place, but the system we have in place right now, I don't always make a python-dateutil release when tzdata gets updated - I haven't yet decided if it's better to spin out the tzdata as its own package or if it's better to just provide a `dateutil update-zoneinfo` function that pulls updated zoneinfo data independent of package updates.

Even if I were spawning a new version of dateutil for every `tzdata` release (they happen about 14-16 times per year), consider that you are using version 2.4.2, which was released in *March 2015*. You probably don't want to be exclusively relying on the time zone data shipped with the `python-dateutil` package if you update it once every 18 months. ;)

@jarondl No problem. I marked this PR and the other two as 2.5.0 anyway, so I wasn't planning on merging them until after the 2.4.1 release, because they all add features rather than fix bugs.

This one especially I wanted to give a bit more time in terms of code review, because there are a lot of ways to do it. I really would have preferred to be able to infer the version from the tzfile itself, but I didn't see any obvious way to do that (there's a version in the MAKEFILE, but I checked old versions of the tzdata file and it wasn't always there, so I don't know if that's stable).

Anyway, I wasn't super happy with the elegance of this, so if you've got a better way to do it, I have zero problem with that.

